When your app creates real analysis records, use Firebase’s server timestamp.

import 'package:cloud_firestore/cloud_firestore.dart';

await FirebaseFirestore.instance
    .collection('users')
    .doc(uid)
    .collection('analyses')
    .add({
  'sport': 'soccer',
  'callOnField': 'foul',
  'decision': 'Inconclusive',
  'confidence': 0,
  'ruleApplied': '',
  'reasoning': '',
  'limitations': '',
  'createdAt': FieldValue.serverTimestamp(),
});

This line is the important part:
'createdAt': FieldValue.serverTimestamp(),

That tells Firebase:
Use the real server time when this document is created.

For backend JavaScript later
createdAt: admin.firestore.FieldValue.serverTimestamp()

or if using modular imports:
createdAt: FieldValue.serverTimestamp()

So your placeholder is okay

Right now you have:
users/randomId/createdAt = date only

Later your real data will be:
users/{uid}/analyses/{analysisId}/createdAt = server timestamp

So you can leave it alone.


Important

Your current users/Auto-ID document will not match your future real user ID. That’s okay. It was only a test placeholder.

The real app will create:
users/{firebaseAuthUserId}/analyses/{analysisId}

Example:
users/a8sD91kLm2/analyses/play001



